### Lambda Expressions in C#

Lambda expressions are anonymous functions that provide a concise way to write inline code blocks.

### Syntax

```csharp
(parameters) => expression_or_statement
```

### Basic Examples

```csharp
// Expression lambda (single expression)
Func<int, int> square = x => x * x;
Func<int, int, int> add = (a, b) => a + b;

// Statement lambda (multiple statements)
Func<int, int> factorial = n =>
{
    int result = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
        result *= i;
    return result;
};

// No parameters
Action greet = () => Console.WriteLine("Hello!");
```

### Lambda with LINQ

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 };

var evens = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0);
var squared = numbers.Select(n => n * n);
var sorted = numbers.OrderByDescending(n => n);
var sum = numbers.Aggregate((a, b) => a + b);
```

### Lambda Types

| Type | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|---------|
| `Func<T, TResult>` | Takes T, returns TResult | `Func<int, int> f = x => x * 2;` |
| `Action<T>` | Takes T, returns void | `Action<string> a = s => Console.WriteLine(s);` |
| `Predicate<T>` | Takes T, returns bool | `Predicate<int> p = x => x > 0;` |

### Capturing Variables (Closures)

Lambdas can capture variables from the enclosing scope:

```csharp
int multiplier = 10;
Func<int, int> multiply = x => x * multiplier;
Console.WriteLine(multiply(5));  // 50

multiplier = 20;
Console.WriteLine(multiply(5));  // 100 (reflects change)
```

### Type Inference

```csharp
// Explicit parameter types
Func<int, int> f1 = (int x) => x + 1;

// Implicit parameter types (most common)
Func<int, int> f2 = (x) => x + 1;
Func<int, int> f3 = x => x + 1;  // Single param, no parens
```

### Discard Parameters (C# 9+)

```csharp
Func<int, int, int> sum = (_, _) => 0;  // Ignore both params
```

> **Key Point:** Lambdas are essential for LINQ queries, event handlers, and functional programming patterns in C#. Expression lambdas (single expression without braces) are more concise than statement lambdas. Be aware of closure semantics when capturing loop variables.

### Event Handlers

```csharp
button.Click += (sender, args) => Console.WriteLine("Clicked!");
```

### Lambda with Tuples

```csharp
var items = new[] { (1, "A"), (2, "B") };
var filtered = items.Where(x => x.Item1 > 1);
```

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Linq;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var numbers = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 };

        // Lambda with Where and Select
        var result = numbers
            .Where(n => n % 2 == 0)
            .Select(n => n * n);

        Console.WriteLine("Even squares: " + string.Join(", ", result));

        // Lambda with FindAll
        var evens = numbers.FindAll(n => n > 4);
        Console.WriteLine("Greater than 4: " + string.Join(", ", evens));
    }
}
